CC   -!- FUNCTION: Substrate-recognition subunit of protein phosphatase 2A
CC       (PP2A) that plays a key role in cell cycle by controlling mitosis entry
CC       and exit (PubMed:39003739). Involved in chromosome clustering during
CC       late mitosis by mediating dephosphorylation of MKI67 (PubMed:39003739).
CC       Essential for serine/threonine-protein phosphatase 2A-mediated
CC       dephosphorylation of WEE1, preventing its ubiquitin-mediated
CC       proteolysis, increasing WEE1 protein levels, and promoting the G2/M
CC       checkpoint (By similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P63151,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:39003739}.
CC   -!- SUBUNIT: PP2A consists of a common heterodimeric core enzyme, composed
CC       of a 36 kDa catalytic subunit (subunit C) and a 65 kDa constant
CC       regulatory subunit (PR65 or subunit A), that associates with a variety
CC       of regulatory subunits (By similarity). Proteins that associate with
CC       the core dimer include three families of regulatory subunits B (the
CC       R2/B/PR55/B55, R3/B''/PR72/PR130/PR59 and R5/B'/B56 families), the 48
CC       kDa variable regulatory subunit, viral proteins, and cell signaling
CC       molecules (By similarity). Interacts with the PP2A C catalytic subunit
CC       PPP2CA (By similarity). Interacts with the PP2A A subunit PPP2R1A (By
CC       similarity). Interacts with TP53 (By similarity). Interacts with IER5
CC       (By similarity). Interacts with MFHAS1; the interaction is direct (By
CC       similarity). Interacts with PABIR1/FAM122A (via its N-terminus); the
CC       interaction is direct and inhibits PP2A activity (By similarity).
CC       Interacts with ARPP19; the interaction is direct and inhibits PP2A
CC       activity (By similarity). Interacts with CRTC3 (PubMed:30611118).
CC       {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P63151, ECO:0000269|PubMed:30611118}.
CC   -!- DOMAIN: Has an extended WD 2 repeat that is important for the
CC       interaction with PPP2R1A. {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P63151}.
CC   -!- DISRUPTION PHENOTYPE: Lethality during late embryonic development
CC       (PubMed:32582689, PubMed:39003739). Embryos are significantly smaller
CC       and display a variety of neural defects such as exencephaly, spina
CC       bifida and cranial vault collapse, as well as syndactyly and severe
CC       epidermal defects; all processes driven by growth and differentiation
CC       of the ectoderm (PubMed:32582689). Embryos have incomplete epidermal
CC       barrier acquisition, associated with thin, poorly differentiated
CC       stratified epithelium with weak attachment to the underlying dermis
CC       (PubMed:32582689). Mitotic cells display increased chromosome
CC       scattering, associated with in the presence of enhanced phosphorylation
CC       and perichromosomal loading of Mki67 (PubMed:39003739).
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32582689, ECO:0000269|PubMed:39003739}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the phosphatase 2A regulatory subunit B family.
CC       {ECO:0000305}.
