CC   -!- FUNCTION: 3-dehydroshikimate dehydratase; part of the qa gene cluster
CC       that mediates the catabolism of quinic acid (QA) and as such, allows
CC       the use of QA as a sole carbon source (PubMed:2525625, PubMed:6458044).
CC       Catalyzes the third reaction in the inducible quinic acid catabolic
CC       pathway by converting dehydroshikimate to protocatechuate
CC       (PubMed:149131). The qa cluster encodes 3 inducible enymes (qa-2, qa-3
CC       and qa-4) catalyzing the first three reactions in the catabolism of
CC       quinic acid to protocatechuic acid (also known as 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic
CC       acid) (Probable). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:2525625, ECO:0000269|PubMed:6458044,
CC       ECO:0000305|PubMed:123642}.
CC   -!- CATALYTIC ACTIVITY:
CC       Reaction=3-dehydroshikimate = 3,4-dihydroxybenzoate + H2O;
CC         Xref=Rhea:RHEA:24848, ChEBI:CHEBI:15377, ChEBI:CHEBI:16630,
CC         ChEBI:CHEBI:36241; EC=4.2.1.118;
CC         Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131};
CC       PhysiologicalDirection=left-to-right; Xref=Rhea:RHEA:24849;
CC         Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131};
CC   -!- ACTIVITY REGULATION: Divalent cations such as Mg(2+), but also MO(2+),
CC       Mn(2+), Ba(2+), and Co(2+) activate the enzyme, whereas monovalent
CC       cations as K(+), Na(+), and NH4(+) decrease its activity slightly.
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131}.
CC   -!- BIOPHYSICOCHEMICAL PROPERTIES:
CC       Kinetic parameters:
CC         KM=0.6 mM for dehydroshikimate {ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131};
CC   -!- PATHWAY: Aromatic compound metabolism; 3,4-dihydroxybenzoate
CC       biosynthesis; 3,4-dihydroxybenzoate from 3-dehydroquinate: step 2/2.
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131}.
CC   -!- SUBUNIT: Monomer. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:149131}.
CC   -!- INDUCTION: Expression is induced in the presence of quinic acid
CC       (PubMed:6458044). The quinic acid (qa) gene cluster is subject to two
CC       levels of gene control: a primary system which responds to the presence
CC       of quinic acid via the qa-1S repressor protein that blocks the qa-1F
CC       activator, and a secondary system which represses transcription of qa
CC       genes in the presence of a preferred carbon source such as glucose
CC       (PubMed:12477937, PubMed:17597928, PubMed:19236936, PubMed:6458044,
CC       PubMed:9279395). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:12477937,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:17597928, ECO:0000269|PubMed:19236936,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:6458044, ECO:0000269|PubMed:9279395}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the bacterial two-domain DSD family.
CC       {ECO:0000305}.
