RN   [2]
RP   FUNCTION, CATALYTIC ACTIVITY, DOMAIN, AND PATHWAY.
RX   PubMed=40137209; DOI=10.3390/jof11030171;
RA   Kong D., Wang X., Liu L.;
RT   "Biosynthesis of a Novel Diketopiperazine Aspkyncin Incorporating a
RT   Kynurenine Unit from Aspergillus aculeatus.";
RL   J. Fungi 11:0-0(2025).
CC   -!- FUNCTION: Nonribosomal peptide synthetase; part of the gene cluster
CC       that mediates the biosynthesis of the diketopiperazine (DKP) aspkyncin
CC       (PubMed:40137209). AacA catalyzes the condensation of two unusual
CC       amino-acids, N-methyl-L-alanine and L-kynurenine (L-Kyn), via the
CC       nucleophilic attack of the secondary amine group of N-methyl-L-alanine
CC       on the thioester of N-methyl-L-alanine-L-Kyn-S-T2, resulting in the
CC       formation of aspkyncin (PubMed:40137209). N-methyl-L-alanine originates
CC       from the methylation of L-alanine by the methyltransferase aacB whereas
CC       L-kynurenine is produced by the indoleamine-2,3-dioxygenase (IDO) that
CC       catalyzes the ring-opening oxidation of L-Trp to form N-formyl-l-
CC       kynurenine, followed by subsequent hydrolyzation to L-kynurenine (L-
CC       Kyn) through an endogenous L-kynurenine formamidase (Probable).
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:40137209, ECO:0000305|PubMed:40137209}.
CC   -!- CATALYTIC ACTIVITY:
CC       Reaction=N-methyl-L-alanine + L-kynurenine + 2 ATP = aspkyncin + 2 AMP
CC         + 2 diphosphate + 2 H(+); Xref=Rhea:RHEA:86051, ChEBI:CHEBI:15378,
CC         ChEBI:CHEBI:30616, ChEBI:CHEBI:33019, ChEBI:CHEBI:57959,
CC         ChEBI:CHEBI:58175, ChEBI:CHEBI:235348, ChEBI:CHEBI:456215;
CC         Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:40137209};
CC       PhysiologicalDirection=left-to-right; Xref=Rhea:RHEA:86052;
CC         Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:40137209};
CC   -!- COFACTOR:
CC       Name=pantetheine 4'-phosphate; Xref=ChEBI:CHEBI:47942;
CC         Evidence={ECO:0000255|PROSITE-ProRule:PRU00258};
CC   -!- PATHWAY: Secondary metabolite biosynthesis.
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:40137209}.
CC   -!- DOMAIN: NRP synthetases are composed of discrete domains (adenylation
CC       (A), thiolation (T) or peptidyl carrier protein (PCP) and condensation
CC       (C) domains) which when grouped together are referred to as a single
CC       module. Each module is responsible for the recognition (via the A
CC       domain) and incorporation of a single amino acid into the growing
CC       peptide product. Thus, an NRP synthetase is generally composed of one
CC       or more modules and can terminate in a thioesterase domain (TE) that
CC       releases the newly synthesized peptide from the enzyme. Occasionally,
CC       epimerase (E) domains (responsible for L- to D- amino acid conversion)
CC       are present within the NRP synthetase. AacA has the following
CC       architecture: A-T-C-A-T. {ECO:0000305|PubMed:40137209}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the NRP synthetase family. {ECO:0000305}.
